  "prompt": "Is Turkey in the Schengen Agreement?",
  "response": "No, Turkey is not part of the Schengen Agreement. The Schengen Agreement is a treaty that led to the creation of Europe's Schengen Area, where internal border checks have largely been abolished. The Schengen Area includes many European Union (EU) member states, as well as a few non-EU countries like Norway, Iceland, Switzerland, and Liechtenstein.\n\nTurkey, while a member of NATO and a candidate for EU membership, is not part of the Schengen Area. As a result, travelers entering Turkey from the Schengen Zone or vice versa are subject to border controls and must adhere to visa requirements based on their nationality.",
